The area also functions as the central commercial and entertainment district of Yamaguchi City, offering many restaurants. Unlike onsen that emerge in the urban centers of prefectural capitals such as {{ill|Kōfu Onsen|ja|甲府温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tottori Onsen|ja|鳥取温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Matsue Shinji Lake Onsen|ja|松江しんじ湖温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Dogo Onsen|ja|道後温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, Misasa Onsen is located within a densely built urban area. Although it lacks the traditional atmosphere of a historic onsen town, several spots exist for nighttime strolls.
The Matsudaya Hotel in the onsen town is reputed as a lodging where patriots of the late Edo period once gathered. In addition, the hotel was selected by critic {{ill|Ishii Hiroko (Critic)|ja|石井宏子 (評論家)|12=draft|12=draft}} as one of “10 Inns to Savor Gourmet Cuisine” and was also listed among “200 Recommended Inns & Communal Baths” by {{ill|Matsuda Tadanori|ja|松田忠徳|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The town places strong emphasis on its foot baths, with five facilities including {{ill|Inoue Park|ja|井上公園|12=draft|12=draft}} (formerly Takada Park). Since October 17, 2005, the Misasa Onsen Distribution Cooperative and {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefectural University|ja|山口県立大学|12=draft|12=draft}} have jointly conducted efficacy tests on these foot baths. In March 2015, Yamaguchi City opened a paid tourist circulation facility called “Fox’s Footprints.”
== Onsen Facilities == * Public Baths – Kawahara-yu (河原の湯) and Kabayu (株湯) * Foot Baths – Kawahara no Yu (河原の湯), Yakushi no Yu (薬師の湯), Kajika no Yu (かじかの湯), Kabayu (株湯) * Hot Spring Drinking Facilities – Yakushi no Yu, Kabayu, and the “Kami-no-Yu” at {{ill|Misasa Shrine|ja|三朝神社|12=draft|12=draft}} In addition, as a municipally operated national lodging facility in Misasa Town, “Brannal Misasa” was established. Its former name was Misasa Onsen Kaikan, which opened in 1963 (Shōwa 38) and was renamed Brannal Misasa in 1995 (Heisei 7). Brannal Misasa was transferred in 2023 (Reiwa 5) to a group company of G-Lion, the designated administrator. Furthermore, there was a communal bath called “Tamahari no Yu” that served both residents and visitors; however, due to aging facilities and an aging workforce, it ceased operations at the end of March 2023. The site of “Tamahari no Yu” is planned to be sold in May 2024 (Reiwa 6) to the G-Lion Group, which intends to construct a high-end ryokan there.
== Surrounding Areas == * {{ill|Santoku Mountain|ja|三徳山|12=draft|12=draft}} (Mitoku-san) and {{ill|Sanbutsu-ji|ja|三仏寺|12=draft|12=draft}} – Along with the Nikkō Heritage Site “Land of Purification of the Six Roots and Healing of the Six Senses” (六根清浄と六感治癒の地) designated by the Agency for Cultural Affairs in 2015, featuring the {{ill|Tōnyūdō|ja|投入堂|12=draft|12=draft}} among others. * {{ill|Shikakan Kei|ja|小鹿渓|12=draft|12=draft}} – A National Scenic Area. * {{ill|Uchibuki Tamagawa|ja|打吹玉川|12=draft|12=draft}} – An Important Traditional Buildings Preservation District. * {{ill|Kurayoshi Park Square|ja|倉吉パークスクエア|12=draft|12=draft}} – Including the Kurayoshi Future Center and the Tottori 20th Century Pear Memorial Museum.
== Access == * Rail: Approximately 20–25 minutes by bus from {{ill|Kurayoshi Station|ja|倉吉駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the JR {{ill|San'in Main Line|ja|山陰本線|12=draft|12=draft}} via {{ill|Hinonmaru Bus|ja|日ノ丸自動車|lt=Hinonmaru Bus|lt_ja=日ノ丸バス|12=draft|12=draft}}. * Bus: Direct bus service for Misasa Onsen / Hawai Onsen. * By Car: Accessible via the {{ill|Sanyō Expressway|ja|山陰自動車道|12=draft|12=draft}} from the Hawai Interchange via National Route 179 and Tottori Prefecture Road 21 (Tottori-Kanago-Kurayoshi Line); alternatively, from the {{ill|Yonago Expressway|ja|米子自動車道|12=draft|12=draft}} via National Routes 313 and 482, National Route 179, and Tottori Prefecture Road 21.
